---
import ArticleLayout from "../../components/ArticleLayout.astro";

const title = "Wave–Particle Duality — Science";
const updated = "Updated: 2026";
---

<ArticleLayout title={title}>
  <article class="page">
    <header>
      <div class="hero-top">
        <a class="back" href="/">← Back to Atlas</a>
        <span class="chip">PHYSICS</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Wave–Particle Duality</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Light and matter can act wave-like or particle-like depending on how the experiment is arranged.</p>
      <p class="subtitle">{updated}</p>
    </header>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Key ideas</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        <div class="card"><h3>One object, different behaviors</h3><p>Electrons can make interference patterns yet arrive as discrete detection events.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>The setup decides what appears</h3><p>A detector that asks “which path?” removes interference and reveals particle-like outcomes.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>Quantum theory unifies both</h3><p>Wave functions evolve continuously; measurements produce discrete events.</p></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Mental model</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
        <li>Send particles one by one through two slits.</li>
        <li>Without path detection, an interference pattern appears over time.</li>
        <li>With path detection, the pattern disappears and behaves classically.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details><summary>Are particles secretly tiny billiard balls?</summary><p>Not in quantum mechanics; classical pictures fail at small scales.</p></details>
        <details><summary>Are waves physically spread like water?</summary><p>Not exactly. The quantum wave encodes probabilities and phase relations.</p></details>
        <details><summary>Why teach this early?</summary><p>It builds intuition for uncertainty, measurement, and modern devices.</p></details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <nav class="footnav">
      <a class="btn" href="/science">← Science index</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/future">Explore Future →</a>
    </nav>
  </article>

</ArticleLayout>
